# Moving ŌĆö coding conventions

These conventions are enforced by ESLint + Prettier where possible. When a rule
is taste-based (not in `eslint.config.mjs`), follow the guidance here.

## General

- Prefer **arrow functions** by default. Use regular `function` only when the framework requires it (e.g. Next.js `default export` for pages, server actions, etc.) or when the function genuinely benefits from hoisting / `this` binding.
- **No one-letter variable names.** Use descriptive, meaningful names for variables, functions, types, hooks, and components. Even loop counters get real names (`index`, `boxIndex`).
- **Prioritize readability over clever code.** If a clever one-liner is harder to read than the verbose version, choose the verbose version.
- **Avoid deeply nested logic.** ESLint enforces `max-depth: 3`. Use early returns, guard clauses, and helper functions before nesting.
- **Extract helper functions when complexity grows.** ESLint enforces `complexity: 8`. If a function trips the warning, extract.
- **Keep files small and focused.** ESLint enforces `max-lines-per-function: 60`. Prefer many small files over a few big ones.
- **Split large components into smaller components.** Same for hooks and utility files ŌĆö focused over kitchen-sink.
- **Avoid premature abstractions.** Don't introduce a layer of indirection until the duplication is real and stable.
- **Follow existing project patterns before introducing new ones.** When in doubt, grep for prior art.
- **Make incremental changes** ŌĆö small, reviewable commits over sweeping rewrites.

## Comments

**Don't add comments by default.** Prefer self-documenting code through clear naming, strong typing, small focused functions, and good file organization. If a piece of code seems to need a comment to explain what it does, first try to make the code itself more readable.

Comments should be rare and only used when they convey information that cannot be expressed through code.

### Allowed comments

- Non-obvious business requirements.
- Framework limitations or workarounds.
- Browser-specific behavior.
- Third-party library limitations.
- Important architectural decisions.
- Real `TODO` markers for tracked future work.

### Avoid

- Comments that restate the code.
- Section separator comments (`// ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ helpers ŌöĆŌöĆŌöĆ`).
- Decorative banners.
- Generated boilerplate left behind by scaffolding.
- JSX comments describing UI elements.
- Comments explaining simple logic.
- Comments that exist only because the code is hard to understand ŌĆö refactor instead.

### When modifying existing files

Remove comments that don't meet the "Allowed" criteria above:

- Comments that repeat what the code already says.
- Section separators.
- Decorative banners.
- Generated/scaffold comments.
- Outdated comments.
- JSX comments that describe UI structure.

Keep an existing comment only if it clearly fits one of the allowed categories.

### Prefer over comments

- Better naming.
- Early returns.
- Smaller functions.
- Extracted helper functions.
- Clear file structure.

The codebase should be understandable without comments. If a piece of code seems to need multiple comments to make sense, refactor the code instead of adding more comments.

## Architecture

The project follows a layered structure. Respect the layer boundaries:

```
src/
  app/          ŌåÉ Next.js routes (Server Components, route handlers)
  features/     ŌåÉ Domain slices (boxes/, items/, ...) ŌĆö components, services, schema fragments
  components/ui/ŌåÉ Atomic UI primitives (shadcn-style)
  lib/          ŌåÉ Cross-cutting concerns (db, env, logger, errors, api wrapper)
  constants/    ŌåÉ Shared enums and constants
```

- **`app/` may import from `features/`, `components/`, `lib/`, `constants/`.**
- **`features/<x>/` may import from `lib/`, `components/`, `constants/`, and within itself.**
- **Features should not import from each other directly** ŌĆö go through their public `index.ts` barrel if you must.
- **`lib/` and `components/ui/` must not import from `features/` or `app/`.**
- Server-only modules (DB clients, services with side effects) start with `import "server-only";` to fail-fast if pulled into a client bundle.

## React

- Prefer **functional components** with the Composition API equivalent ŌĆö props in, JSX out.
- Prefer **composition over large components**. If a component does three things, it's three components.
- Keep component responsibilities focused ŌĆö one screen / one widget / one decision per component.
- Avoid large JSX trees in a single file. If the JSX is hard to scan, extract subtrees.
- Extract reusable logic into hooks when it appears more than twice.
- **Server Components by default**, Client Components (`"use client"`) only when state, effects, or browser APIs are needed.

## Styling

- **No inline styles.** Use Tailwind utility classes.
- Use the reusable UI primitives from `@/components/ui/*` when one exists.
- For class composition, use the `cn()` helper from `@/lib/utils`.
- Keep styling consistent across screens ŌĆö the brand palette lives in `globals.css` as CSS variables and is exposed via shadcn theme tokens.
- Tailwind class order is sorted automatically by `prettier-plugin-tailwindcss` ŌĆö don't fight it.

## TypeScript

- **Strict typing.** `strict: true` and `noUncheckedIndexedAccess: true` are on. Don't escape via `any`.
- **Prefer `import type` for type-only imports** ŌĆö enforced by `@typescript-eslint/consistent-type-imports`.
- **Avoid `any`.** If you genuinely need it, leave a comment explaining why and use `// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` so it's a deliberate, searchable exception.
- **Prefer explicit return types on exported functions** ŌĆö improves readability and prevents surprises across module boundaries.
- For component props, prefer `type Props = { ... }` (not `interface`) unless extension/declaration-merging is actually needed.

## Imports

ESLint sorts and groups imports automatically (`simple-import-sort`). The order is:

1. Side-effect imports (`import "server-only"`)
2. React (`react`, `react-dom`)
3. Next.js (`next`, `next/*`)
4. Other external libraries (`zod`, `clsx`, `drizzle-orm`, ...)
5. Internal infra (`@/lib`, `@/utils`, `@/services`, `@/hooks`, `@/configs`, `@/constants`, `@/types`)
6. Feature/domain imports (`@/features/*`)
7. UI components (`@/components/*`)
8. Other internal `@/*` imports
9. Parent imports (`..`)
10. Sibling/index imports (`./...`)
11. Style imports (`*.css`, `*.scss`)

Don't hand-organize imports ŌĆö save the file and let ESLint do it.

## Database (Drizzle + SQLite)

- Schema lives in `src/lib/db/schema/<table>.ts`, re-exported from `schema/index.ts`.
- Generate migrations with `pnpm db:generate`. Never hand-edit `0000_*.sql` and friends.
- For things Drizzle-Kit can't express (triggers, custom indexes), use `drizzle-kit generate --custom` and commit the SQL.
- Apply migrations with `pnpm db:migrate`.
- DB queries belong in `features/<x>/services/*-service.ts`, never in route handlers or components.

## API routes

- Use the `withApi(fn)` wrapper from `@/lib/api/handler` for every route ŌĆö it standardizes error mapping (Zod, AppError, unknown) and response shape.
- Validate request bodies with Zod schemas defined alongside the service.
- Route handlers are thin: parse ŌåÆ call service ŌåÆ return. Business logic stays in the service layer.

## Errors and logging

- Throw `AppError` (from `@/lib/errors`) with the right factory (`badRequest`, `notFound`, `unauthorized`, `internal`) for known failure modes.
- Use the `logger` from `@/lib/logger` instead of `console.log`. `console.warn` and `console.error` are allowed for genuine warning/error paths only.

## Things to avoid

- **`no-nested-ternary`** ŌĆö refactor to `if`/early return or extract a helper.
- **`no-else-return`** ŌĆö once you `return` in an `if` branch, drop the `else`.
- **`prefer-template`** ŌĆö `\`hello ${name}\`` instead of `"hello " + name`.
- **`object-shorthand`** ŌĆö `{ name }` instead of `{ name: name }`.
- **`eqeqeq`** ŌĆö always `===` / `!==`.
- **`curly`** ŌĆö even single-statement `if` bodies get braces.
